<br>
That's not to infere that all of the patrons were of the unscrupelous sort.  This particular establishment carried with it a bit of fame and infamy.  The Lusty Oar, or better known to the holy types as Caldor's Feigned Brewery, attracted many who wished to momentarily bask in the aura of the one who defeated Lucin-- the evil paladin of Freeport and grandfather to the current owner-- then get more faced than a gnome at a high elf nudist colony.  <br>
<br>
Rodlac stopped his whistling as a new face appeared at the bar.  One could always tell a newbie by the same mistake.<br>
<br>
&quot;Gimmie a Caldor House, lad,&quot; a thick beard and beady eyes said under a helmet half the wearer's weight.<br>
<br>
Rodlac handed him a tankard.  The beard slugged back the brew and looked toward the distance with the air of a man who has just decided that his mother in law isn't all that bad after all.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Gah,&quot; the beard gahhed, &quot;Yer father wasn't to ken on the process was he?&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;I'm afraid my husband never was much of a brewer, how about a Bleeding Brain, on the house,&quot;  a soulty voice that seemed to reach into areas of the libido not wholley appropriet to be reached into slinked from behind Rodlac.  The beard and beady eyes clashed with a sudden reddening of the barely perceviable area under the helm.  It muttered a hurried thanks, a lecterous leer, and a hasty retreat.  <br>
<br>
Hard to blaim him.  Tantrika had lost none of her appeal since the Freeport incident.  Luxourious blue skin, supple bosom, hair that flowed like cascading shadows even in still wind, and legs that did indeed go all the way up.  Essentially, the other half of the tavern's success, and Rodlac's mother.  <br>
<br>
Tantrika adored her son.  He looked much like his father-- tall, slender, blonde wavey hair with a touch of dark blue at the tips from his half dark elven heritage, and the same peircing blue eyes that suggested a soft heart, a warm shoulder, and with concent the possibility of a hot bath with a little elven wine.  He did however lack the muscle tone, battle scars, and dedication to a noble cause that made his father famous.  <br>
<br>
The problem with being the son of a hero and nearly three quarters elven is that not only do you have to live in your father's shadow all your life, but you also get a few extra centeries to think about it.  <br>
<br>
As far as Rodlac was concerned, those centeries were best put off untill the end.  But, what kind of story would that be?<br>
<br>
The door slammed open.  Not an unusual occurence in and of itself considering most trolls and ogres think of this as a form of knocking.  Unusual is the holy paladin who entered emblazed in full regail (most paladins, as a rule, enter in dark hoods and avoid eye contact).  Also unusual was the many soldiers who followed.<br>
<br>
&quot;In the name of our God, we find this estableshment in contempt.&quot; the paladin shouted.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye, ye tried the house brew yerself too then,&quot; the beard bellowed.  <br>
<br>
