<br>
The tavern fell silent.  The shamblings of the skeletol waiter the only sound as it moved about collecting empty mugs.<br>
<br>
&quot;Nice job, Big B, Rodlac said at last.  He held out his hand to the troll.  He recieved a cold glare.<br>
<br>
&quot;Cal-Door wud not need ass-sentance fer one like dat.&quot;  The troll returned to his dark corner. <br>
<br>
Rodlac moved closer to his mother with a questioning look on his face.  &quot;Bloodclot yerns to journey once more, as he did with your father.&quot;  Tantrika spoke wistfully. Rodlac remembered the look from her stories when he was a child.  <br>
<br>
&quot;As do you,&quot; Rodlac noted.  &quot;So go ahead, I'll take care of the tavern.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tantrika shook her head.  Wisps of silver swayed over the blue skin of her face.  &quot;We must all go together..<br>
<br>
&quot;What for?  We make plenty of money, we don't need to adventure for riches.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Not for riches, sweetie.&quot;  Tantrika scraped her thumbnail over the bar top unconciouly.  Her other hand snaked behind her back, fingers weaving spells of death and pestalince that, if she had not removed the heart runes of, could immidietly empty the back room of all patrions... as well as several acres of foilege.  <br>
<br>
&quot;A mute point&quot;  A coy smile.  &quot;Tomarrow there will come an end to this place.&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;The paladins?&quot;  Rodlac snickered. <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes dear.  The paladins in Freeport are a bored, tenatious lot tricked by thier god to destroy what brings pleasure.  They will return with seige weapons.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Isn't that a bt extreme?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Silly boy,&quot; Tantrika giggled. &quot;Zealots are extremist by definition.  And BLoodclot injured more than just his pride.&quot;  She spun around and faced the crowd.  &quot;Gentlemen,&quot; the assasins and necromancers scoffed and banged mugs against the tables, the holy men and honest merchants looked around with guilt.  &quot;As of now, the Lusty Oar has retired.  Free drinks for the rest of the night, however I do suggest leaving at dawn.&quot;<br>
<br>
She turned back to Rodlac.  &quot;Pack up tonight, we leave when the moon tells us.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Luna speak sooon&quot; Bloodclot's voice boomed above Rodlac's ear.  <br>
<br>
She shrugged.  &quot;Before the mourn, Luna will not answer more than that.&quot;<br>
<br>
Bloodclot nodded.  &quot;Will pack much food fer journey.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No, Shaman.  We hunt and move light, like the old days.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Cal-door hunt dat journey.  Now Rod-Lack bring fud?&quot;  Bloodclot looked the boy over.  &quot;Pack too packs, me carry.&quot;  Bloodclot marched through a side door to his room, a makeshift partition in the stable.  The smell of hair and horse sweat reminded him of home.<br>
<br>
&quot;Miss mudda.&quot;  He sighed, gathering stores of salted meats and fruits into his packs.  He paused a moment, looked to the sky and spoke.  &quot;Cal-Door, mentor friend...&quot;  He cleared his throat and looked to theground.  &quot;Cal, journey complete, promise over, got dat?&quot;  <br>
<br>
He grasped a large mallet that, according to rumor, was gilted in the melted scales of a silver dragon.  Bloodclot knew what silver dragon tasted like, this was not it.  &quot;Shudda taken da other choice, much more easy.&quot;<br>
<br>
------ Midsummer's Nightmare -----<br>
<br>
Tantrika sat near the fire, equipment by her feet.  She leaned back in the wooden chair, worn down by years and claws.  The celebrations had calmed to low muttering.  Tantrika's pet deader had pulled all the kegs to front room to allow the patrons to serve themselves.  She occasionally sipped on a mug of tea as she ran a stone over a short sword.  Unneccessary due to the runes blazed into the blade, preventing dulling of the edge.  <br>
<br>
The act brought back memories.  Katlain, the warrior drow who died protecting Freeport from Lucan.  She had sacrificed herself to give Caldor life.  Love of a friend, Kat said, was more powerful than any bond of servitude or marraige.  <br>
<br>
Caldor's voice wispered behind her eyes.  &quot;Ain't those different names for the same thing?&quot;  <br>
<br>
She smiled to herself.  Cal, her sweet fool, the cynical athiest monk.  His last breath was proposal.  Glancing up, she noticed the skeletal waiter watching her.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Sit, Adore.  You will journey with us.&quot;  Adore sat on the floor, by her feet.  Pin pricks of blue light watched her unwavering.  His body remained completely still.  Adore had remained at her side for as long as Rodlac could remember.  From the short time Rod spent in Nerriak, he could tell that necromancers did not typically name thier animated companions, nor were they kept preserved for more than a few days at a time.  Yet this one seemed to be a pet of sorts, possibly even a silent friend.  <br>
<br>
But Rod did not think of this as he stood before the window in his room.  The stars shinned ominously dark this night.  A large bundle layed upon his bed.  A shape, a griffon, swooped before the moon... full, tinted red, hanging ponderously in the sky.  Sat heavy, the matress of his bed giving little give under his weight, and thought of the journey ahead.  <br>
<br>
&quot;This is bullshit,&quot; he said to himself.  &quot;Even my own mother does'nt understand.&quot;  He slammed his fist into the bedpost.  It cracked from the force, nearly in half with a solid outline of his knuckles pressed into the wood.  &quot;I am not my father!&quot;  His screams echoed back to him as if the air about him had turned to thick fog, distorting his own voice, sending a chill through his spine.  <br>
<br>
He sighed, continued to stare at the moon.  A dark shadow began to creep over, from top to bottom, an eye winking at him.  A tingle ran through his body, anticipation or anxiety?<br>
<br>
He stood, lifted his bag (a grotisque grafting of leathery hide that gave the impression of an evil gaze but did seem to make his load a little lighter), and made his way to the front room.<br>
<br>
Tantrika greeted her son as he entered the room.  &quot;Luna has given us leave.  We journey once Bloodclot joins us.&quot;  She stood up.  The sword hung holstered over her back, worn only in memory of Katlain. Attacked under both wrist, rigged to leap into her hands with a flick of wrist, her daggers quivered in anticipation.  The runes that made the blades bite deep and true also granted them limited awareness.  They were now aware that their fast would soon end.  <br>
<br>
A tug at her wrist gained her attention.  A gnome, small for even his race, gazed at her with sorrow in his eyes. Chomskie, beardless under a black bandana tied about his neck,bright eyes under bushy white brows, and approxemetly a dozen or so weapons hidden about his person.  <br>
<br>
&quot;So den, you really do mean to retire?&quot;  Tantrika nodded.  &quot;Ack! And what about our business agreement, huh blue buns?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Our... agreement?&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;Aye, I leave you an yer friends be, and take my price from the lushes.  We've been doing it fer years now.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I believe you forgot to mention this arangment to us.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah... well, no harm done.&quot;  Chomskie shrugged.  &quot;Still though, what am I to do fer money now?&quot;<br>
<br>
Bloodclot's door slammed open.  He carried two packs, each wrapped around his massive shoulders rather than across the back.  He hefted the silver hammer, smiled.  &quot;Lady blink.  Go now?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Just a moment dear shaman,&quot; Tantrika said.  &quot;I've but one last item to conclude.&quot;  She looked down at the gnome.  &quot;It is not my concern.  Now go, little one.&quot;<br>
<br>
Chimskie's eyes lit up.  &quot;I'll go with yer party.  Ken make quite a few silvers slaying and plundering.  I need just a moment to ready myself.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Me like idea.&quot;  He smacked his lips.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sorry, little one.  We make haste this moment.&quot;  Chomskie groaned.  &quot;However, take what pilage remains here and find a new benifactor.&quot;  Tantrika, sweet and kind as she is, was still a necromancer to the core.  <br>
<br>
&quot;And these drunks?  You leave them to the coming army?<br>
<br>
&quot;They have been warned.&quot;  She shrugged.  With that, she turned to the egress and strode with deep purpose.  Rodlac and Bloodclot followed.  At the door, Rodlac stopped to glance back one last time.  He gave a deep sigh and walked out. <br>
<br>
Shoulders hunched, Chomsky went to work cleaning the money pouches of the remaining guest.  He climbed the stairs to check the rooms.  A few gold, a decent sword, some locket of gold that would sell for a nice price once the picture of pair of twin babies was scratched off.  <br>
<br>
He approached a door near the end of the hall.  He reached for the knob when sound caught his ears.  Inside, sloshing of water and a female voice mutterring to herself too quiet to hear.  He carefully creaked the door open.  <br>
<br>
Inside, lounging in a tub of steaming bubbles, a beauty with black hair slick with soap.  &quot;ah,&quot; Chomskie thought.  &quot;The injured girl.  Forgot she was still here.&quot;<br>
<br>
Chomskie silently closed the door.  He treaded toward the next room.  A thought struck him.  The tavern had been earned of the coming army, but she would have no idea.  He stopped in his tracks, torn between looting and the memory of soap bubbles clinging like lovers to the gently sloping curve of her amble bosom.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Damn this sence of chivalry.&quot;  Chomskie turned back to the room with the girl.  He knocked on the door.  <br>
<br>
-----<br>
<br>
Rodlac slumped down against a tree.  Bloodclot glared at him with a mix of disapointment and anger.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Not time fer camp, get up&quot;<br>
<br>
Tantrika placed her hand on his massive arm.  &quot;It is his first time, let him rest.  His endourance will rise in time.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Cal-Door wud not need rest.  He make me beg fer rest.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tantrika glanced toward her son already in sleep's grasp.  &quot;Dear shaman, do you forget your first journey?  How far from the swamp did you make it?&quot;<br>
<br>
Bloodclot looked away.  &quot;Fine, me make fire fer the night.&quot;  He pictured a structure of logs glazed with fire.&quot;  Tantrika pulled a blanket from her pack and covered her son.  <br>
<br>
From the east, sounds of catapaults slinging flaming pitch against the tavern could be heard.  Creaks from logs slowly pulling away from supports were audible.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Good bye,&quot; Tantrika whispered.  Adore stared at the flaming horizen, a wistful impression in it's eyes.  <br>
<br>
End Chapter I<br>
